{{Other uses|14th Battalion (Australia)}} {{Infobox military unit |unit_name=2/14th Battalion |image=AWM 081092 2 14 Bn Atherton Tablelands 1944.jpg |alt=Soldiers slowly advance up a hill along the side of a waterway |caption=2/14th Battalion personnel training on the Atherton Tablelands, September 1944 |country=Australia |allegiance= |type=[[Infantry]] |branch=[[Australian Army]] |dates=1940–46 |specialization= |command_structure=[[21st Brigade (Australia)|21st Brigade]], [[7th Division (Australia)|7th Division]] |size=~800–900 personnel{{#tag:ref|By the start of World War II, the authorised strength of an Australian infantry battalion was 910 men all ranks; however, later in the war it fell to 803.{{sfn|Palazzo|2004|p=94}}|group=Note}} |current_commander= |garrison= |ceremonial_chief= |ceremonial_chief_label= |nickname= |motto= |colors= |identification_symbol=[[File:2 14th Battalion AIF Unit Colour Patch.PNG|100px|alt=A grey diamond organisational symbol with a multi-coloured rectangle inside it]] |identification_symbol_label=[[Unit Colour Patch]] |march= |mascot= |battles=[[World War II]] * [[Syria–Lebanon campaign]] * [[New Guinea campaign]] * [[Finisterre Range campaign]] * [[Battle of Balikpapan (1945)]] |notable_commanders=[[Ralph Honner]] |anniversaries= }} The '''2/14th Battalion''' was an [[infantry]] [[battalion]] of the [[Australian Army]] that served during [[World War II]]. Part of the [[21st Brigade (Australia)|21st Brigade]], [[7th Division (Australia)|7th Division]], the battalion was raised from [[Second Australian Imperial Force]] volunteers drawn mainly from the state of Victoria. After completing training in Australia in 1940, the battalion deployed to the Middle East where it was stationed in Egypt and Palestine before it saw action against the [[Vichy France|Vichy French]] in [[Syria–Lebanon campaign|Syria]] in June and July 1941, in a short lived campaign. Garrison duties in Lebanon followed before the battalion was withdrawn to Australia in early 1942 as Australian forces were concentrated in the Pacific to respond to the threat posed by Japan's entry into the war.
After a short period of training in Australia, the battalion was deployed to [[New Guinea campaign|New Guinea]] in August 1942 as the Australians sent reinforcements to the [[Kokoda Track campaign|Kokoda Track]] to fight against Japanese forces that had been advancing towards Port Moresby. After the Japanese exhausted their supplies and began to fall back towards their beachheads on the north coast, the 2/14th saw further action around [[Battle of Buna–Gona|Gona]]. In September 1943, after a period of re-organisation in Australia, the battalion took part in the [[Salamaua–Lae campaign|advance on Lae]] as the Allies went on the offensive in New Guinea, before taking part in the fighting in the Markham and Ramu Valleys of the [[Finisterre Range campaign]]. The battalion's final involvement in the war came in the [[Battle of Balikpapan (1945)|landing on Balikpapan]] in 1945. The 2/14th was disbanded after the war, in early 1946.
==History==
===Formation=== The 2/14th Battalion{{#tag:ref|The numerical designation of 2nd AIF units was prefixed by "2/", which was used to set them apart from [[Australian Army Reserve|Militia]] units with corresponding numerical designations.{{sfn|Long|1952|p=51}} |group=Note}} was raised on 26 April 1940 at [[Puckapunyal, Victoria]],<ref name=AWM>{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11265.asp|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110402031353/https://www.awm.gov.au/units/unit_11265.asp|title=2/14th Battalion |work=Second World War, 1939–1945 units |publisher=Australian War Memorial |accessdate=18 April 2011|archivedate=2 April 2011}}</ref> shortly after the start of [[World War II]] as part of the all-volunteer [[Second Australian Imperial Force]] (2nd AIF), which was established at the time from personnel that had volunteered to serve in combat overseas.{{sfn|Grey|2008|p=146}} The battalion was assigned to the [[21st Brigade (Australia)|21st Brigade]], [[7th Division (Australia)|7th Division]],<ref name="AWM" /> and would remain part of this formation throughout its existence.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=6762&Tab=Sup&Titl=2/14%20Infantry%20Battalion |title=2/14 Infantry Battalion: Superiors |publisher=Orders of Battle.com |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> It had an authorised strength of around 900 personnel, and most of those were drawn from the state of [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], although some were allocated from other states later as reinforcements. Many of the battalion's initial recruits had previous military experience, having served in the [[Australian Army Reserve|Militia]] prior to volunteering for the 2nd AIF, with the majority having to relinquish rank to transfer. Officially the battalion's average age on formation was 29, although the battalion historian, William Russell, asserts that this is not necessarily accurate as men were found to have altered their ages both up (from as young as 15) and down (from as old as 55) upon recruitment.{{sfn|Russell|1948|pp=3–4}} In keeping with 2nd AIF recruitment practices, there were many pairs of brothers who were early recruits; there was even one case of a father and son who served in the same [[platoon]].{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=4}}
Soon after battalion headquarters was established, the battalion's first [[commanding officer]], Lieutenant Colonel William Cannon,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.awm.gov.au/units/people_1080733.asp |title=VX13432 Lieutenant Colonel William George Cannon |publisher=Australian War Memorial |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> began choosing his officers, who then set about the task of forming their own [[Company (military unit)|companies]] and platoons, as the unit structure was built up around four rifle companies&nbsp;– designated 'A' through to 'D'{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=3}}&nbsp;– with a battalion headquarters and a headquarters company consisting of several specialist platoons including signals, pioneer, anti-aircraft, transport, administration and mortars. The battalion's companies were formed largely along territorial lines, with 'A' Company being drawn mainly from the [[Mildura]] and north-eastern regions of Victoria, while 'B' Company was drawn from [[Geelong]], the [[Western District (Victoria)|Western District]], [[Prahran, Victoria|Prahran]], [[Brighton, Victoria|Brighton]] and the [[Mornington Peninsula]]. 'C' Company consisted largely of men from [[Ballarat]] and Melbourne's inner suburbs, and men of Scottish ancestry, while those of Irish ancestry formed 'D' Company.{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=3}} Once the battalion's complement of men had arrived at Puckapunyal and formation was complete, basic training began in May 1940.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=26}} On 18 August, the battalion was presented its regimental colours in a ceremony by members of the [[14th Battalion (Australia)|14th Battalion]], who had served during [[World War I]].{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=18}} This was done in order to establish links with the units of the [[First Australian Imperial Force]], and later, in early October, the 2/14th Battalion changed its [[Unit Colour Patch]] from a black over blue diamond to the yellow and blue rectangle of its earlier counterpart.{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=13}} Shortly after this, although still only partially trained, the battalion received orders to deploy overseas, and on 18 October the men embarked upon the [[RMS Aquitania|''Aquitania'']] in [[Sydney, New South Wales]], bound for the [[Middle East]].{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=26}}{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=14}}
===Middle East=== Travelling via India, the battalion arrived at Kantara, in [[Egypt]] on 25 November 1940 and were transported to Julius Camp in [[Palestine (region)|Palestine]],{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=29}}{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=19}} where the soldiers undertook further training.<ref name=AWM/> Later, they were moved to Dimra in January 1941,{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=27}} before being sent in April to [[Mersa Matruh]], in Egypt, to defend against a possible German attack there during the [[Siege of Tobruk]].{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=34}} Although no German attack came there, during their time at Maaten Bagush the battalion was subjected to aerial attack. It remained there until the end of May when the battalion was relieved by a South African battalion.{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=37}} The 21st Brigade then returned to Palestine to begin preparations for operations in [[Syria]] and [[Lebanon]] against the [[Vichy France|Vichy French]] in order to prevent the area from falling into the hands of the Germans who could then have launched an attack on the [[Suez Canal]] from there, or captured the oilfields in [[Persia]] (present-day Iran).{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=38}}
The 2/14th Battalion's involvement in the [[Syria–Lebanon campaign]] began on the night of 7/8 June when the unit advanced across the Palestine border from Hanita and attacked Vichy outposts around the village of Alma Chaab.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|pp=42–43}} Following this, the battalion advanced along the coast towards [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]], from where it evicted the French defenders before forcing a crossing over the [[Battle of the Litani River|Litani River]].{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=46}} On 11 June, the 21st Brigade's advance towards [[Sidon]] came up against determined resistance around the Zahrani River, at Merdjayoun. The 2/14th Battalion found themselves up against troops from the [[French Foreign Legion]]'s [[6th Foreign Infantry Regiment]]. For the next few days the battalion came under attack from Vichy French aircraft and artillery before being committed to a flanking action on 15 June. Conducting a {{convert|30|km|mi|adj=on}} march during the heat of the day, the Australians approached Sidon through the mountains but arrived just after the town fell to the [[2/27th Battalion (Australia)|2/27th Battalion]].{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=48}}
[[File:AWM 008249 2 14th Bn refs Syria 1941.jpg|right|thumb|2/14th Battalion reinforcements in Syria, 13 June 1941|alt=Soldiers in tropical uniforms climb on to a truck]]
Following this, on 17 June,{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=48}} the battalion was moved to the central sector of the Allied advance in order to reinforce the [[2/31st Battalion (Australia)|2/31st Battalion]], attached to the [[25th Brigade (Australia)|25th Brigade]], which was holding off a Vichy French counter-attack at [[Battle of Jezzine (1941)|Jezzine]].<ref name=AWM/> After [[Damascus]] was captured on 22 June, the 2/14th Battalion was committed to the fighting to secure a number of features on Mount Kharatt, high ground north-east of the town which dominated the surrounding area.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=52}} These attacks proved unsuccessful, and quite costly for the 2/14th, with 12 killed and 47 wounded on 24 June.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=61}} The fighting around Jezzine continued until 29 June when the French began to withdraw.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=66}} After this, the Australians regained the initiative and on 2 July the 2/14th Battalion left Jezzine to begin preparations for the [[Battle of Damour]], to which it was committed on 5 July 1941.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=65}} Between then and 9 July, the 2/14th were involved in a number of attacks, capturing French positions on Hills 243 and 567.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|pp=68–69}}
On 12 July, an [[armistice]] came into effect, ending the fighting.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=70}} Following this, the 2/14th Battalion was initially used to conduct battlefield clearance tasks before moving to [[Beirut]] where the men were used as garrison troops overseeing the repatriation of captured Vichy soldiers to France.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=73}} Later, in September, the battalion was transferred to the north to construct defensive positions near [[Tripoli, Lebanon|Tripoli]] in Lebanon.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=74}} In December 1941, following the Japanese attacks on [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|Pearl Harbor]] and in [[Battle of Malaya|Malaya]], the decision was made to bring the [[6th Division (Australia)|6th]] and 7th Divisions back to Australia. In early January 1942, the 7th Division left Syria, where it had been undertaking garrison duties, and returned to Palestine.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=77}} The 2/14th were moved to a camp near [[Jerusalem]], and during this time command of the battalion passed to Lieutenant Colonel Arthur Key, who had previously commanded the [[2/8th Battalion (Australia)|2/8th Battalion]].{{sfn|Dornan|1999|pp=77–78}} On 30 January 1942 the 2/14th Battalion embarked on the transport [[SS Île de France|''Ile de France'']] from Port Tewfik in Egypt, bound for Australia.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|pp=78–81}} The 2/14th's casualties during its deployment to the Middle East were 21 killed, 94 wounded and 11 captured.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=248}}
===Kokoda Track=== The battalion returned to Australia via [[Bombay]], where the infantrymen were transferred to the troopship [[SS City of Paris (1920)|''City of Paris'']] in early February. They arrived in [[Adelaide, South Australia]], on 24 March 1942.<ref name=AWM/> After this a period of leave followed, and then the battalion undertook defensive duties and training around [[Yandina, Queensland]],{{sfn|Dornan|1999|pp=85–86}} before being dispatched along with the rest of the 7th Division to [[New Guinea]] where the situation on the [[Kokoda Track campaign|Kokoda Track]] was becoming critical for the Australians as the Japanese advanced towards [[Port Moresby]].{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=183}}
On 13 August 1942, the 21st Brigade, including the 2/14th Battalion, disembarked in Port Moresby.<ref name=AWM/> Three days later, 16 August, the battalion was transported on trucks to Ilolo before marching to Uberi, reaching Myola on 21 August.{{sfn|Keogh|1965|pp=183–184}} On 25 August, the battalion received orders to relieve the severely depleted [[39th Battalion (Australia)|39th Battalion]], which was holding the Japanese at [[Battle of Isurava|Isurava]]. Due to a shortage of supplies it was only possible for one company to move at a time, and as a result 'C' Company was dispatched to Isurava first,{{sfn|Dornan|1999|pp=106–107}} while 'B' and 'D' Companies were dispatched to [[Alola]] and 'A' Company moved to Templeton's Crossing.{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=206}} 'C' Company subsequently reached the 39th's position late in the evening of 26 August.{{sfn|McAllester|1990|p=238}} The following day, the Japanese launched a fresh offensive with three battalions from the [[144th Infantry Regiment (Imperial Japanese Army)|144th Infantry Regiment]],{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=206}} and throughout the day a number of minor engagements took place. On 27 August, the Japanese offensive began in earnest as the 39th Battalion's positions around Isurava were subjected to heavy mortar and artillery fire. Japanese infantry broke into the position through the gaps between one of company's depleted platoons, but the situation was restored by two Australian counter-attacks.<ref name=AWM2>{{cite web|url= http://www.awm.gov.au/units/event_342.asp |title=Battle of Isurava |publisher=Australian War Memorial |accessdate=19 April 2011}}</ref>
[[File:9 platoon 2-14Bn 16Aug42.jpg|right|thumb| Men from 9 Platoon, 'A' Company, 2/14th Battalion at Kokoda on 16 August 1942|alt=A group of weary soldiers in a jungle scene]]
The rest of the 2/14th Battalion arrived on 28 August amidst continuing fighting, bringing with them a {{convert|3|in|mm|adj=on}} mortar for indirect fire support.{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=207}} The 39th Battalion then moved to the rear, but remained in support of the 2/14th in order to help repel the next wave of the Japanese attack. By 29 August, the Japanese had about six battalions around Isurava,{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=207}} and in the morning fresh attacks succeeded in breaking into the 2/14th's position with 'C' Company, on the battalion's right, being forced to give ground.<ref name=AWM2/> With the situation critical, the Australians launched a counter-attack. As a part of this attack, Private [[Bruce Kingsbury]] charged the Japanese, firing his [[Bren light machine gun]] from the hip, killing at least 30 of them and forcing others to withdraw. Although Kingsbury was subsequently killed by a sniper, his actions allowed the Australians to briefly regain their positions and later he was posthumously awarded the [[Victoria Cross]], Australia's highest military decoration. Further attacks during the day, however, forced the battalion to fall back {{convert|1|km|mi}} down the track.<ref name=AWM2/>
On 30 August, the Japanese began threatening the 2/14th's left flank from the high ground situated there, and as another attack put the battalion's rear in jeopardy, the battalion was forced to give more ground. At this point, the brigade commander, Brigadier [[Arnold Potts]], authorised a withdrawal to Alola.{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=207}} With the Japanese pressing against their rear guard, over the course of the following fortnight, the battalion fought a series of delaying actions and fighting withdrawals towards Ioribaiwa and Imita Ridge. By the time it reached Imita Ridge, the 2/14th was so depleted that it was amalgamated with the 2/16th Battalion to form a composite battalion of just over 300 men,{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=211}} and as the 21st Brigade prepared to make a final stand, the battalions of the 25th Brigade arrived to relieve them.{{sfn|Brune|2004|p=238}}{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=215}} Following this, the composite battalion was withdrawn from the line on 16 September. The 2/14th Battalion had begun the Kokoda campaign with 546 men, but upon arriving at Uberi, where they had been placed in reserve, there were only 88 men available, of whom only three were officers.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=156}} Casualties were high, with 110 men being killed in action, with two more dying of their wounds and another four being killed in accidents. A further 132 were also wounded.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=249}}
===Gona=== Following the 21st Brigade's relief, the fighting in New Guinea began to turn in favour of the Allies, as the Japanese, having exhausted their supplies, began to fall back towards their beachheads on the north coast. By November 1942, although the 2/14th had been reformed at [[Koitaki]], near Port Moresby, it was still not up to full strength, with a total of only 341 men of all ranks.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=171}} Nevertheless, the situation in New Guinea meant that the 21st Brigade was needed to help capture the Japanese beachhead around [[Battle of Buna-Gona|Gona]] on the north-eastern coast.{{sfn|Brune|2004|p=435}} The 2/14th Battalion, under the command of Lieutenant Colonel Hugh Challen who had replaced Key in late September,{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=174}} after the latter had been captured and executed by the Japanese following the fighting around Isurava,{{sfn|Williams|2012|p=112}} was placed in the vanguard of the brigade's move, being air transported to [[Popondetta]] on 25 November.{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=257}}
Organised into three half-strength companies, the following day the battalion began the {{convert|32|km|mi|adj=on}} march towards Gona. On 29 November, the 2/14th attacked along the coast to the east of Gona. The Japanese positions were well-concealed and amidst strong resistance the 2/14th suffered heavy casualties, losing 13 killed and 23 wounded.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=184}} Early in the morning on 30 November the battalion lost another three killed before it launched a well-planned deliberate attack on the remaining Japanese fortified position. For only two minor casualties, the 2/14th forced the Japanese defenders to abandon their positions and managed to break through to the beach, securing about {{convert|1.5|km|mi}} along the coast.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|pp=184–185}}
On 8 December, a reinforced platoon from the 2/14th was ordered to conduct a reconnaissance around Haddy's Village, {{convert|2|km|mi}} west of Gona, where the Japanese had landed reinforcements on 6 December. Under the command of Lieutenant Bob Dougherty, the platoon launched a surprise attack against the numerically superior force. In the hand-to-hand fighting that followed over 90 Japanese were killed or wounded, while six men from the 2/14th were wounded. The attack proved a success and enabled the Australians around Gona to attack without concern about being engaged by the Japanese reinforcements. Gona was subsequently taken on 9 December. Dougherty, who was recommended for the Victoria Cross for his actions, was killed leading a patrol around the village on 11 December.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|pp=186–187}} The battalion remained in the area until 8 January 1943, by which time there were only 21 fit personnel left. They were subsequently returned to Australia.<ref name=AWM/> Casualties during the fighting around Buna, Gona and Sanananda amounted to 50 killed in action or died of wounds or accidentally, as well as 88 wounded.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=249}}
===Lae and the Finisterres=== By the time that the 21st Brigade arrived back in Australia, it was heavily depleted, with only 44 per cent of its authorised strength.{{sfn|Dexter|1961|p=268}} The 2/14th subsequently underwent a period of rebuilding around [[Ravenshoe]], in Queensland, in preparation for further operations.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=163}} During this time the units of the 7th Division were converted to the [[Jungle division|"jungle" divisional establishment]], which saw a reduction in the 2/14th Battalion's authorised strength to just over 800 men.{{sfn|Palazzo|2004|p=94}}{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=165}} As the battalion was brought back up to strength, in July there was a change of command. On 5 July, Lieutenant Colonel [[Ralph Honner]], who had previously commanded the 39th Battalion during the fighting on the Kokoda Track, replaced Challen as commanding officer.<ref name=orders1>{{cite web|url=http://www.ordersofbattle.com/UnitData.aspx?UniX=6762&Tab=App&Titl=2/14%20Infantry%20Battalion |title=2/14 Infantry Battalion: Appointments |publisher=Orders of Battle.com |accessdate=18 April 2011}}</ref> In August, along with the rest of the 21st Brigade the battalion moved to Port Moresby where it undertook training for the next month in preparation for the [[Salamaua–Lae campaign]]. However, the battalion was destined to only take a limited role in the campaign, and on 15 September it was dispatched to the airfields at [[Nadzab]] to relieve the [[US Army]]'s [[503rd Infantry Regiment (United States)|503rd Parachute Infantry Regiment]] and defend the vital airfields from possible Japanese attack.<ref name=AWM/>{{sfn|Dexter|1961|p=385}}
[[File:Dougherty AWM018982.jpg|thumb|left|Brigadier [[Ivan Dougherty]] (left), 21st Brigade commander, with his battalion commanders. Lieutenant Colonel [[Philip Rhoden]] of the 2/14th is fourth from the left.]] After this, the 2/14th was committed to the advance into the [[Finisterre Range campaign|Markham Valley and Finisterre Range]], in the vanguard of the 21st Brigade's [[Battle of Dumpu|advance from Kaiapit to Dumpu]] in late September and early October.<ref name=AWM/> Moving through the 2/16th Battalion's position and advancing on to Marawasa, the 2/14th left the Markham Valley and proceeded into the [[Ramu Valley]].{{sfn|Bradley|2004|p=46}} The 2/14th then moved on the 2/16th's right flank, protecting it from any Japanese attacks that might have eventuated from the north. On 4 October 1943, the battalion reached Wampun village. It was there that the battalion's commanding officer, Honner, was seriously wounded when he moved beyond the main defensive position in order to personally carry out a reconnaissance of the surrounding area.{{sfn|Bradley|2004|p=46}} A platoon was sent in to extricate Honner as the Japanese began advancing on his position, and after directing a company-level attack against the Japanese, Honner handed over command to Captain Ian Hamilton, commander of 'C' Company, who served as acting commander briefly until Major Mert Lee arrived from brigade headquarters. Lee remained in acting command until the battalion second-in-command, Major [[Philip Rhoden]], returned from a staff course to officially take over command of the battalion as a lieutenant colonel in December.<ref name=orders1/>{{sfn|Bradley|2004|pp=48, 67–69}}
Throughout early 1944, the battalion was mainly involved in patrol operations in support of the 21st Brigade's advance up the Faria River to capture the Japanese positions around on the Kankiryo Saddle during the [[Battle of Shaggy Ridge]].{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=345}} As a part of this effort, the battalion's most significant engagement came on 11 October 1943 when 9 Platoon, under Lieutenant Noel Pallier, destroyed a Japanese company in capturing a ridge that overlooked the valley. The Japanese company had been threatening to cut off the supply line of the 2/27th Battalion, which was leading the 21st Brigade's advance and the following day, heavy fighting took place around [[Battle of John's Knoll–Trevor's Ridge|John's Knoll and Trevor's Ridge]].{{sfn|Bradley|2004|pp=66–84}} After this, the battalion undertook mainly patrol actions in the following weeks, these actions varied in size from small groups to company-sized forces, and varied in length from one day to up to a week.{{sfn|Russell|1948|pp=238–240}} In late November, the battalion relieve the 2/25th Battalion around John's Knoll, marching {{convert|17|mi|km}}. From there, they occupied an outpost position opposite a strong Japanese position, against which they clashed several times throughout December until being withdrawn to the rear around the Lakes area in late December, and then Port Moresby in early January 1944.{{sfn|Russell|1948|pp=242–252}} Although there were only limited engagements with the Japanese during the four months that the 2/14th were involved in the campaign, the battalion still suffered heavily with 958 men being evacuated due to illness or accidental injury during this time. Of these, four died and a further 546 were permanently removed from the theatre.{{sfn|Russell|1948|pp=252–253}} In contrast, battle casualties during this time amounted to seven killed in action, three died of wounds and 25 wounded.{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=321}}{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=249}}
===Borneo=== [[File:AWM 111238 2 14 Bn Manggar Borneo July 1945.jpg|thumb|right|A [[Ordnance ML 3 inch mortar|3-inch mortar]] crew in action around Manggar airstrip, 5 July 1945|alt=A mortar crew in action]]
After being withdrawn back to Australia in March 1944,<ref name=AWM/> the units of the 7th Division received six weeks' leave before reforming on the [[Atherton Tablelands]] in Queensland.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=211}} Following this the 2/14th Battalion undertook a period of training before finally being committed to their last campaign of the war in mid-1945. This campaign saw them take part in the amphibious landings at [[Battle of Balikpapan (1945)|Balikpapan]] on 1 July 1945.{{sfn|Keogh|1965|pp=461–462}} During the initial landings early on 1 July, the 2/14th came ashore at the wrong place, landing at Yellow Beach when it had been scheduled to land at Green Beach.{{sfn|Long|1963|p=514}} Nevertheless, the landing was largely unopposed and after 45 minutes of reorganisation the Australians were able to establish themselves at their correct form up point and begin the advance to their first objective: the bridge over the Klandasan Besar. Advancing unopposed they crossed the bridge and at nightfall dug-in in front of the Stalkudo ridge, along the Vasey Highway.{{sfn|Long|1963|p=514}} The following day, the battalion captured the Sepinggang airstrip as the 21st Brigade began the advance to the east.{{sfn|Long|1963|p=520}}{{sfn||Keogh|1965|p=462}} The 2/27th Battalion subsequently relieved the 2/14th at Sepinggang and on 3 July, the battalion began to move towards the [[Manggar]] airstrip. The 21st Brigade then came up against stronger opposition near the Batakan Ketjil River,{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=463}} which held them up until the evening.{{sfn|Long|1963|p=522}}
The following day the 2/14th resumed its advance towards Manggar and after crossing the river and beginning to move across the strip the battalion's lead company began to receive artillery fire from Japanese coastal defence guns.{{sfn|Long|1963|p=525}} Naval gunfire support was called in to provide [[counter-battery fire]], but this was only partially effective and the following day air support and tanks were brought it.{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=463}} For the next three days minor infantry actions were undertaken around the periphery of the position while direct and indirect fire support was used to reduce the position, with a view to limiting casualties amongst the infantry.{{sfn|Long|1963|p=527}} Finally, on 9 July, the battalion attacked the two remaining Japanese positions, which had been named "Frost" and "Brown" by the Australians. Supported by a naval bombardment and [[Consolidated Liberator|Liberator]] heavy bombers which dropped [[napalm]], two companies from the 2/14th Battalion captured the position where it found over 100 Japanese dead along with a number of artillery pieces including two 120&nbsp;mm naval guns and four 75&nbsp;mm high-angle guns, as well as numerous heavy mortars and machine-guns.{{sfn|Long|1963|pp=529–530}} This represented the last of the 2/14th Battalion's major combat actions of the war.<ref name=AWM/> The 21st Brigade subsequently captured Sambodja and then as the tempo of operations wound down in anticipation of the end of the war, the Australians began conducting patrol operations in the interior, stretching towards the 25th Brigade's area along the Milford Highway.{{sfn|Keogh|1965|p=463}} The battalion's casualties in its final campaign of the war amounted to 21 killed and 41 wounded.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=250}}
===Disbandment=== [[File:AWM 120854 2 14 Bn Celebes 1945.jpg|thumb|right|Troops from the 2/14th Battalion at Makassar, Celebes, October 1945|alt=Soldiers marching under arms with rifles at the slope file past a drum band]]
Following the cessation of hostilities in August 1945, the 2/14th Battalion remained on Borneo until October 1945 when it was moved to [[Makassar]] in the [[Sulawesi|Celebes Islands]] (present-day Sulawesi, Indonesia). The battalion's personnel arrived there on 1 October 1945 but shortly thereafter the 2/14th was transported by sea to [[Pare-Pare]], arriving there on 5 October.{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=311}} While there the battalion undertook garrison duties, guarding Japanese prisoners of war and maintaining administration and law and order until the Dutch were in a position to re-assert colonial rule. Despite the complex political situation, the 2/14th Battalion managed to achieve this without violence and on 5 January 1946 the 50th Battalion, [[Royal Netherlands East Indies Army]], began to arrive to relieve them. This was completed by 17 January.{{sfn|Russell|1948|pp=315–316}} On 22 January 1946 the battalion embarked on {{HMAS|Kanimbla|1936|6}}, bound for Australia.<ref name=AWM/> Upon arrival in [[Brisbane, Queensland]], the [[Demobilisation of the Australian military after World War II|demobilisation process]] began and the battalion's ranks were quickly reduced. Finally, on 22 February 1946, at [[Victoria Barracks, Brisbane|Victoria Barracks]] the final paperwork was signed off and the battalion was disbanded.{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=316}}
During the course of the war, a total of 2,990 men served in the battalion; of these 222 were killed in action or died of wounds, or of illness or accident on active service. A further 378 men from the 2/14th were wounded in action, while 11 men became prisoners of war.{{sfn|Johnston|2005|p=248}}{{#tag:ref|There is some discrepancy in the various sources regarding the 2/14th's casualties. Russell provides the figures of 151 killed in action, 31 missing in action, 25 died of wounds, 19 died of illness and 378 wounded in action,{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=321}} while the Australian War Memorial provides totals of 245 dead and 379 wounded.<ref name=AWM/>|group=Note}} The vast majority of these casualties came during the fighting around Kokoda where the battalion suffered 248 battle casualties.{{sfn|Russell|1948|p=321}} For their service during the war, members of the 2/14th received the following gallantry and distinguished service decorations: one Victoria Cross, four [[Military Cross]]es, three [[Distinguished Conduct Medal]]s, 19 [[Military Medal]]s, one [[British Empire Medal]] and 44 [[Mentioned in Despatches|Mentions in Despatches]]. In addition, one member was appointed as an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]].<ref name=AWM/>{{sfn|McAllester|1990|pp=373–375}} One [[Section (military unit)|section]] from the battalion, 7 Section from 9 Platoon, 'A' Company, is believed to be, according to Dornan, "the most highly decorated section in Australian and British military history".{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=191}} Of the 11 men that were assigned to 7 Section when it was first formed in 1940, one of them received the Victoria Cross, one received a Distinguished Conduct Medal and four received the Military Medal.{{sfn|Dornan|1999|p=191}}
==Commanders== The following officers served as commanding officer of the 2/14th Battalion:<ref name=AWM/><ref name=orders1/>{{sfn|McAllester|1990|p=2}} * Lieutenant Colonel William Cannon (1940–42); * Lieutenant Colonel Arthur Key (1942); * Lieutenant Colonel Hugh Challen (1942–43); * Lieutenant Colonel [[Ralph Honner]] (1943); * Lieutenant Colonel [[Philip Rhoden]] (1943–46).
==Battle honours== The 2/14th Battalion received the following [[battle honour]]s for its service during the war:<ref name=AWM/> * [[North African campaign|North Africa]], [[Syria-Lebanon campaign|Syria 1941]], [[Syria-Lebanon campaign|Syrian Frontier]], [[Syria-Lebanon campaign|Adlun]], [[Battle of Jezzine (1941)|Jezzine]], [[Battle of Damour|Damour]], [[South West Pacific Area|South-West Pacific 1942–1945]], [[Kokoda Track campaign|Kokoda Trail]], [[Battle of Isurava|Isurava]], [[Battle of Eora Creek–Templeton's Crossing|Eora Creek–Templeton's Crossing I]], [[Battle of Mission Ridge – Brigade Hill|Efogi–Menari]], [[Battle of Ioribaiwa|Ioribaiwa]], [[Battle of Buna-Gona|Buna–Gona]], [[Battle of Buna-Gona|Gona]], [[Battle of Buna-Gona|Amboga River]], [[Salamaua-Lae campaign|Lae–Nadzab]], [[New Guinea campaign|Liberation of Australian New Guinea]], [[Markham and Ramu Valley&nbsp;– Finisterre Range campaign|Ramu Valley]], [[Battle of Shaggy Ridge|Shaggy Ridge]], [[Borneo campaign (1945)|Borneo 1945]], and [[Battle of Balikpapan (1945)|Balikpapan]].
